animal.description: Hi there my name is Beast! Don't let my name fool you, I am actually quite sweet, and am even a little shy sometimes when I meet new people. I may need time to warm up to strangers and in new situations, but I am easy to walk on leash, and enjoy gentle pets once I know you. I have lived with another dog and done well, but we do not know my history with cats or kids. I came into the shelter with the following medical notes: FAS (fear, anxiety, and stress)- Anti-anxiety medication was initiated to help ease the transition period into the shelter environment. This behavior may improve once in a stable home environment. Please see your veterinarian after adopting to discuss further behavioral recommendations such as professional training and possible continuation of this medication. Cryptorchid (one testicle did not descend), which was corrected when Beast was neutered. One of Beast's housemates tested positive for heartworm disease. At this time, Beast has tested negative, but it is very important that he begins heartworm preventatives. Heartworms are transmitted through the bite of mosquitos, and not through interactions with infected dogs. Please see your veterinarian for further diagnostic and treatment options. Underweight- At this time Beast was found to be gaining weight and exhibiting a good appetite.

animal.description:
Who doesn't love a DQ Blizzard??? I don't know ANYONE who will turn one down! Certainly not the RESCUE chicks!!! They LOVE SOME ICE CREAM!!
Now you can have a Blizzard all day long! Just adopt me!
But, of course, let me tell you about WHY you want to adopt me ;)
I came from a high kill shelter in West TX, living minute to minute wondering when they would kill me... BUT my fortunes turned around when the rescue said they would save me (and three others from the same place).
I am AMAZING, I must have had someone who loved me once, they trained me to SIT, GIVE PAW, LAY DOWN. I am a very respectful boy too. I play well with others, I LOVE my people!

I have a lot to offer the right family (older children only please), you must know the husky breed. We are smart, active and escape artists. We don't WANT to leave but it is part of our nature- so you need to keep me safe and monitor me closely so I don't accidentally get lost.
If you are committed, I AM committed too!
Look me up, get my digits and APPLY!!! now GO!!!

Local adoption fee is $200 (in MA only)

animal.description:
This stunning guy is Django

Django is a flat coat retriever mix who is 5 months old and currently weighs 28 lbs. He is a very sweet boy who gets along well with other dogs, kids and even likes cats. He loves to run and play and really would like a backyard at his furever home! A furry sibling to play with would be a bonus! Django is crate trained, rides well in car and is ready to find his furever home! Please remember, puppies need a lot of time, patience, love, structure and positive reinforcement. If you have that to give and want to meet Django, please fill out an application!

Application available at https://www.pawsofloverescue.com/adoption-application. Adoption fee of $275 includes neuter/spay, microchip, heartworm testing, deworming, vaccinations, and other necessary procedures. Applications without a phone number will not be processed.Applications can be found online at www.pawsofloverescue.com, under the adopt tab. We require an approved application before a meet and greet is set up.

animal.description:
Fudgey is an approximate 7 month old corgi mix fostered in Indian River County, FL. Although he's a cutie, he's no lapdog. He's rough and tumble and gives his foster brother and sisters a run for their money. He requires a very active home with a playful dog that matches his energy. He's an exuberant and fun- loving puppy. He loves walks, playing with toys, and wrestling with other dogs. He needs to learn manners and is still in the habit of jumping up on your legs and nipping as a puppy does. He also does get under your feet and can easily trip you if you aren't paying attention. He isn't fully pottt-trained and he does submissively urinates at times which he should outgrow. He is ok in a crate BUT quite loud which he makes it known that he's unhappy. His bark is loud and he can be quite barky at a lot of things. Fudgey is up to date on vaccines, neutered and heartworm negative.

Applications will only be considered for Fudgey if the following requirements are met:



Property with fenced yard (not a dog park)



Must have another playful dog with like energy in the home



Experienced dog owner who has trained a puppy in past



Someone who is home often and has time to train a puppy.



Active home

animal.description:
Meet our newest handsome guy, Woody! A real hunk, right?!? Not only is Woody a good looking guy, he quite special too! Woody is deaf. Now we know what you might be thinking, “how will that ever work?!” Well, let us tell you a little about him....

Woody is a year and a half old, and has the best personality. He’s a real good cuddler too! And smart! Did we mention he knows many commands?! He knows his sit, stay, down, paw, and wait commands. Woody is fully potty trained and crate trained as well. 

Woody is an energetic, fun loving boy, who just loves to play! He also does well with other female dogs! Woody would truly make a wonderful addition to an active family.

animal.description: Charlie is a Border Collie mix who will be 11 years old in April. His life changed a year ago when his owner was married to someone with children. Unfortunately, Charlie has not taken well to the children despite all efforts to make it work. He is an extremely smart, very sweet, loving man. Charlie’s favorites include: belly rubs, behind the ear scritches, treats, watching you cook (in case of surprise snacks, of course), being towel dried, his toy lizard, and his favorite ball. His dislikes include: loud noises, thunderstorms, having his feet groomed, squeakers, and young children.. He has a Thundervest that helps with thunderstorms and fireworks. He would do best in a home where there are no children or young active animals.  He’s fully house trained, knows basic dog commands (sit, stay, outside, down, drop it, and can give you left and right paws when asked) and he’s very good at communicating what he needs.

animal.description: Bernie is an Alaskan Husky that we estimate to be about a year old. He is very energetic and rambunctious and would love to redirect that energy into a basic obedience class with his new family. Bernie was brought in as a stray so we don't know much about him, except that he loves to run and has a lot of energy! He will need to be leashed when outside of the house or kept in a yard with a tall fence, as he does jump up. We don't know if he would dig out of a yard, but keep that possibility in mind. Bernie is a young guy and has tendencies of a young dog like jumping on people and occasionally being a bit mouthy (not biting, just open mouth play) and lots of barking! He would love to redirect this energy into an obedience class so he can grow up to be a well mannered dog! We do not know how Bernie would do with other pets, he does seem to love his female neighbor dog here at the shelter, but we don't know if he will get along with all dogs. We also don't know how Bernie would do with cats, pocket pets or livestock. Please take great care if you have other pets when introducing them Bernie. Alaskan huskies tend to have high prey drives, and may unfortunately think your cat is something to be chased. If you have an active lifestyle and the time it takes to train a young dog, give us a call! Bernie is excited to meet his new forever family.

animal.description: 01/30/21 Maggie May was brought back to the shelter because she did not do well with the younger child in the house. Because of this we are requiring that Maggie May goes to a home without children under 12 years old. She was said to do very well with the 14 year old child in the house. Her previous owner stated that Maggie May has difficulties distinguishing between when children are playing and when they are posing as a threat. They also stated that Maggie May does NOT like when people have their hoods up and takes awhile to warm up to strangers. They also said that Maggie May did good with about 50% of the dogs she met but for the other 50% she was more defensive and would bark at them. She did however get along well with the other dog in the house. Maggie May is said to understand sit, no, down, and is good at walking on a leash. Her previous owners said she did great hiking and went on many adventures out in the snow! 01/05/21 Maggie May was surrendered to the shelter because her previous owner could no longer provide her with adequate care. Per her previous owner Maggie is a very timid girl who will need time to warm up. She barks and growls at strangers of both sexes, is said to be shy around women and fearful around men. Maggie is still young and is learning manners and commands; time and patience will be key with Maggie. A basic obedience course would benefit Maggie in commands and confidence and help her bond with her new owner. Maggie is said to be house broken, pad trained, and kennel trained, however with her age and timidness accidents may happen. Maggie is said to be friendly around babies, has not been around children, and is said to be friendly around dogs. Due to Maggie's fearfulness we are requiring she go to a home without children under the age of 5 years. Maggie is in need of a patient home that wil bring her confidence out.
animal.name: MAGGIE MAY

animal.description: See the write up below from Patrick's foster Patrick is in foster and has been for quite some time, he is crate trained, house broken for the most part (once he understands where the door out is) , walks good on a leash, bike rides, plays ball and knows most basic commands (heel, sit, stay, come, down, stop, calm, place, leave it, drop it, kennel IN, touch, bite your toys, and paw) and is also basket muzzle trained, overall he is a real good boy. He is a guy that enjoys a daily bike ride or jog or nice long walk so he will need an active person or family. At present he goes on a nice 1.5 - 2 mile a day bike ride in the evening when its cooler and he enjoys a nice slow pace he trots so cute. He is a tad bit OCD and thrives with a routine and structure in his life. He does have some separation anxiety but has since been put on a low dose of daily medication (Prozac) which has helped tremendously with that, when I leave he is in his crate and I try not to let him see me leave the house and then he is fine. The perfect home for him would be a somewhat low key household, fenced yard, no cats, if children must be older maybe 10 and up, his favorite thing is to chase lizards in the back yard or play ball with you. He can be a snuggly guy too once his energy is drained. He does know how to swim but will not go in the pool unless I ask him too, and then only for a quick go around to cool off, he is not that confident about it yet. Patrick does great walking with most dogs and hanging out working on commands with them outside or inside he has his favorite friend my very neutral female dog, he likes her the best, he can be somewhat scared of new dogs and has to have a slow intro to strange dogs (he would not be a good candidate for the dog park) . He likes ppl and is ok with strangers but also would have person give some treats and have a slow introduction at first as well.

animal.description: Hi there! Thanks for checking me out. I'm a little nervous when I first meet new people, but I think I just need some time to get out of my shell. So, sit with me for a couple minutes and allow me to sniff and get to know you. Once I'm comfortable I'll allow the leashing and get ready for our walk! I love walks, I enjoy sniffing (and peeing) on everything!! I tolerate handling from my handlers but I'm unsure how to really react to it. So, I'll keep still until it's all over then I'll just do a quick shake-off and go find other things to explore. I met some other larger dogs while I was here and I'm not sure how to react to them! We both sniffed each other, said hi but I didn't really know what to do after that? So, I stood still for a couple seconds and once they walked away, so did I. I believe my perfect home would be a calm, relaxing home with not too much activity going around me. I'd like a nice couch to settle on, a good blanket to nap on and a good hooman to sleep on!! I hope to meet you soon.

animal.description: A189467 Poppy is an adorable pittie puppy that is currently in a foster home and will be ready to go home with a family on February 1st! Her foster mom says that She is very outgoing and social, loves people and all the animals in the house. Poppy was the first puppy to engage in play with my adult dogs. She does have a tendency to chase the cats but it's been only playful so far. My cats are not super-disciplinary, so they tend to allow a lot. She can be a bit of an instigator at play time but is not a bully. She likes to push Roxy's buttons quite a bit. Poppy is also the most vocal of the siblings. She does not like being separated from people at bedtime. She will cry and scratch at the door, but we've been very disciplined about not responding to her cries. Because of this, she does settle within about 5 minutes. I get the impression that, while she is outgoing, she will also look to her handler a bit for confidence. This litter of pups are looking for pet parents that are ready and willing to put in the work for proper socialization, potty training, obedience training and snuggles! Families with other pups are a huge plus! These pups are expected to be approximately 50-60 lbs full grown. If you are interested in learning more about this foster pet, please contact the Foster Care Coordinator at fosterpets@talgov.com and reference the Animal ID number at the beginning of this post.

animal.description: Cinder_A204526 Cinder is a 2-1/2-year-old, intact female, blue bindle and white bully/heeler mix that weighs 50 pounds. She was brought in by her former owner on 02/01/21 because they could no longer care for her. Cinder has been a bit down on her luck; this is the third time she has been returned to our facility in less than a year due to NO fault of her own. Cinder did not live with her former owner long, but they did share with us that she is house trained, knows the sit command and takes food gently from your hand. Cinder is super-smart and is eager to please! She'd make a great dog for an active person or family with older, dog-savvy kids. She would do best in a home that has a back yard so she can get some exercise. She loves to be with people and most of all, loves attention! She always greets us here at the shelter with a wagging tail! Cinder had a traumatic experience while living with first former owner; she was visiting with another dog and everything was fine for the first few hours and then all of a sudden, she was attacked. She is a bit leery around dogs now, but we feel that she could live with one again with a proper introduction. If you have another dog and are interested in adopting Cinder, call us at 801-399-8244 to set up an appointment to bring your dog in for a meet and greet. She's neutral toward cats. Cinder's $89 adoption fee includes a $40 voucher to be used TOWARD HER SPAY, WHICH, BY LAW, MUST BE DONE WITHIN 30 DAYS of adoption. It also includes her leash, collar, microchip, up-to-date booster vaccine and rabies vaccine. Weber County Animal Services 1373 North 750 West Ogden, Utah 84404 801-399-8244

animal.description: Hi, my name is URSULA and I would love to meet you. I am a Spayed Female Great Pyrenees mix. The shelter staff think I am about 3 years old. I have been at the shelter since Jan 25, 2021. Meet Ursula! This beautiful pup came to the shelter as a stray so shelter staff and volunteers are still getting to know her. Personality: Ursula is a very sweet but nervous girl. Once she has warmed up, she demands your attention and pets with a dainty paw. She would benefit from having a family that has experience or has done research on shy/fearful dogs. History: Her history with other dogs, cats, and small mammals is unknown. We always recommend SLOW and CAREFUL introductions over time to any resident pets. Energy levels: Ursula is a younger pup that will need daily exercise to keep her happy and healthy! Having a fairly active family would be great. Ideal home/Family: Ideally, Ursula would love to have a large FULLY FENCED yard that she can wander. Due to her timid behavior, everyone in the home should be present to meet with her. Are you the little mermaid to this Ursula? Come down and meet her today!!

animal.description: Hi, my name is PRINCESS and I would love to meet you. I am a Spayed Female Pit Bull Terrier mix. The shelter staff think I am about 1 year and 1 month old. I have been at the shelter since Jan 27, 2021. Meet Princess! This beautiful girl came to the shelter because her family could no longer care for her. Personality: Princess is a sweet love, that is a little nervous here in the shelter environment. Once she warms up, she wants to explore and settle in for some snuggles! History: According to her previous family, she has been around other dogs of various sizes. Her history with cats and other small mammals is unknown. We always recommend SLOW and CAREFUL introductions over TIME with any resident pets. Energy levels: Princess is still a young pup, so once she is comfortable, she will be ready to go! She will need daily exercise and would benefit from working with a qualified trainer. Ideal home: She would LOVE a large fenced yard to get out her young pittie energy! Due to her previous history, she should not be left unattended, and is not suited for dog parks or other off-leash activities. Ideal Family: Princess is looking for a dog experienced home that is ready to scoot over and make some room on the couch for her! She needs a family who will give her the time and space to build confidence and gain trust. Everyone in the home should be present to meet with her. Is this the perfect princess for your castle? Come down and meet her today!

animal.description: Woof, woof! I'm so excited you're thinking about adopting a new fur-ever family member! Here are a few things that may help you with your big decision. First, dogs just want to be happy and feel loved. Living inside and being a part of the family is really important to us. A lot of the things you need as humans to stay happy and healthy, us dogs need too. We depend on you for things like vet visits, nutritious food, clean water, social and play time with people and other pets, training classes, toys, and of course, lots of love and attention! Regular baths, nail trims and grooming help us to look and feel our best, while monthly flea and heartworm prevention help us to stay healthy. Did you know that depending on our size and breed, dogs can live up to 20 years? Just think of the wonderful life we could have together!

animal.description:
Meet Alvin Cash the Dobie!

Any dobie fans out there? We hope you love them as much as we do! Alvin Cash is a purebred Doberman looking for some love from his furever family. He is 4 years old and approx 60 lbs.This distinguished Doberman is out of the puppy stage but still has plenty of energy for a jogging or hiking buddy. He would be the perfect adventure friend.His favorite activities are going for walks and car rides (and he is well mannered at both). Cash also enjoys snuggling and head pets.He is very thoughtful and calm. He is not very playful. He does well with other dogs, but would do well on his own.He is observant and would love to be part of a quiet home.He will need a calm,confident owner with consistent leadership.He'll need more than just a walk around the block to keep him satisfied.He would love to go on hikes and take trips to the beach. He loves going to the beach.Dobermans thrive on exercise,athletic activities, and a job to keep their mind stimulated. He will sit for treats and affection and could easily be taught more commands.Cash has been with males and female dogs. All sizes.He’s shy,but will play with a dog once he warms up. He is obedient and is eager to please his people. He always wants to be near you. He is potty trained and crate trained. He is people friendly, dog friendly, and kid friendly. He has not been cat tested, so unsure how’d he be around cats. He is such a smart and beautiful young boy. He is a real charmer. He would love a yard to stretch his long legs in and he’s observed to be a great family pet! This sweetheart is ready for his new pack!

He is currently being fostered in Houston,TX and is eligible to travel 2/06 once he finds the perfect home!

For any inquires or questions please contact violet@threelittlepittiesrescue.org

To apply for this gentle sweetheart please fill out an application in order to be considered: https://petstablished.com/adoption_form/30285/generic

Our Adoption Facility is located at 2210 Laffoon Trail Madisonville, KY 42431. We are open for the public to view our adoptable animals. However, there are strict guidelines we ask everyone to adhere to in order to maintain the safety of our customers and staff. All visits will be curbside ONLY. There will be NO entry into the facility at this time.
Please note that all intakes will remain by appointment only and curbside only.

Our visiting hours will be Monday-Saturday 1:00 p.m. – 3:00 p.m.

Our employees will wear a face covering for your entire visit. We encourage our visitors to also wear a face covering for your safety as well as our staff’s safety.

You may continue to view our adoptable animals on petango.com and submit your application through the same site!

Please call us 270-821-8965 or email us at info@hopkinscountyhumanesociety.com.

animal.description:
Rocky has been neutered, microchipped, vaccinated, and has tested positive for heartworms. 

Behavior assessment included:
	
1.  Kennel Approach – Excitable response to presence in cage. Jumped at kennel door

2.  Possession – gives up easily, overall playful attitude. Loves tennis balls. Knows “release"

3.  Touch/Handling – can touch all over. Seeks attention.

4.  Food – indifferent or friendly, can take bowl, will sit/wait for food. 

5.  Correction – slow to correct but follows. Pulls a lot needs leash work.

6.  Dominance – Melts under slight pressure/submissive layed all the way down.

7.  Dog to Dog Intro - intro with male Akita– interested, hackles raised, but tail wagging, raised one paw to other dog. Playbows, rolled over to let other dog sniff.

8.  Overall Behavior – Playful, friendly

Additional Notes: Knows sit, knows release for toys, lays, stay, paw


Available for adoption, foster, or rescue at:

Jefferson Parish Animal Shelter - Westbank
2701 Lapalco Blvd; Harvey, LA 70058
504-349-5111 

Please provide ID number when visiting shelter. Thanks!

animal.description:
COCO is a 4 year old 14 pound Lhasa Apso mixed with Shih Tzu.

She is a super friendly, energetic dog that lives to go for long walks. She greets everyone she meets, people and dogs of all sizes and she is always ready to play. 

Coco is very food motivated therefore real easy to train. At home she needs to be next to her person. She won't like being in another room if your watching TV or doing something without her. Curling up on the couch is her favorite pastime. At night sleeping on the bed is a must so please be prepared and open to sharing your bed. She sleeps quietly through the night. 

Coco will need help with housebreaking. She hasn't quite gotten the hang of it. She does go on pads but also has accidents. Definitely do not plan to crate her 
 as she won't have it and she'll let you know.

Coco would thrive with someone who is active and someone who has the time and patience to work with her. Please no children and please no roommates.

Due to Covid and inclement winter weather, Coco is only available for adoption in New York City. All meet and greets will happen by her foster home in Manhattan. To meet her, please go to our website and fill out an application: www.beastlyrescue.org/application

animal.description:
Hello Friends! My name is Booker, and I'm a good and happy boy who is ready to go to my forever home. I'm five years old and weigh 40 pounds. My friends at Wish Bone describe me as small in stature for a Tree Walker Coonhound...after all, good things come in small packages! I do need to pack on some pounds, so healthy treats would be welcome!

I'm a typical hound who always use my nose to scan my environment for interesting information. I'm a friendly boy who should be good with kids over age six. Based on my behavior at Wish Bone, I'm a bit dog-selective.

My minimum adoption fee is $265 plus a $12 fee, if 4 months or older, for rabies registration for McLean County residents. 

I have been neutered, microchipped, vaccinated, heartworm checked, dewormed, and is on flea and heartworm preventatives.

To be considered for adoption, you must first submit the application found at:

animal.description:
Violet is living in a foster home. Submit an application from our website and then make an appointment to meet her.

Violet is not eligible for foster and will be a straight adoption.

Age: ~2 years 
Weight: ~58lbs
Housebroken: Yes
Crate trained: 
Dog sociability: Friendly! Has loved making new friends in playgroup and does well with similarly sized playful dogs. She is friendly on leash, but is strong and will pull towards other dogs to say 'hello!'
Cat sociability: Unknown
Kids: Unknown but can be mouthy (play bites) so only recommended for older kids/teenagers
Ideal home: Violet is an adolescent and active dog who is ready for an active home! She enjoys daily mental and physical enrichment to be her best self. She is very playful with other dogs and may do well in a home with an equally playful (and tolerant!) dog pal. 

Violet is hoping to be someone's forever adventure buddy. There's so much that she loves about life. She loves jumping in the car and going on long hikes and sniffing out new places. She has a rather passionate liking of warmth. She will seek out rays of sunshine to lay in, and knows where all of the heat vents are in the house to lay in front of and on. On a sunny day, she can be found sun-bathing outside. If you're not sure where the warmest spot in your house is, she'll find it for you! She LOVES to play with other dogs and would love to go to a forever home with an energetic doggie sibling! After a long day of playing and adventure, she loves nothing more than to cuddle up with her humans and snore the night away. She'll never fail to surprise you with all the different ways she'll find to cuddle up next to you.


Violet's adoption fee is 300. She is spayed, up to date on core vaccines, microchipped and heartworm negative. Violet came to us with severe demodex mange, a treatable skin condition. Her skin has improved incredibly while in foster and her adopter will need to continue to monitor. If her demodex reappears, future medication needs would be the responsibility of her adopter.

***We are receiving a much higher than usual number of adoption applications. We ask that you please be patient and someone will be in touch via email within 72 hours. Please do not email us unless you have not received a response in 72 hours. Please only fill out one adoption application. ***

My adoption fee is $175.

Hanover Humane will only be adopting me to a home in Hanover County, Virginia or a locality that is part of the Richmond, Virginia metropolitan area.

I'm a big happy boy...about 80 lbs worth. Not only is it easy to see that I have boxer in me, anyone familiar with the breed will also see that I've got that goofy boxer personality. I'm loveable, sweet, and love to be with people.

 I've been neutered/spayed, am current on all of my vaccinations (DHLPP, Bordetella and Rabies), tested for heartworms (and am negative) and put on heartworm preventative, and microchipped.  My new owner will receive a month of free pet health insurance at adoption.

animal.description:
PLEASE READ THE ENTIRE BIO ON THIS DOG BEFORE REQUESTING AN APPLICATION.  MANY OF OUR DOGS HAVE STRICT REQUIREMENTS FOR THEIR ADOPTION.

8 month old male Chihuahua mix, about 6 pounds. Born May 24, 2020 at the rescue. Cadet (and his brother, Trooper) are a great combination of playful and snuggles. He can race around the house chasing and playing with his brother and the other dogs. But then he can be a super snuggler under the blankets the rest of the time. He is super smart, a tad independent and a bit less active than his brother. He is crate trained, uses the doggie door and is learning about the leash. He is very long legged and a bit on the delicate/fragile side. So jumping from high places should not happen! Young children under 12 are not recommended. Dogs bigger than 12 pounds also not recommended. He is a tad afraid of strangers, but warms up when they become friends. Cadet is the little nugget that we had to bottle feed as a young pup because he was not able to compete with his siblings for a nipple. Foster Mindi did a great job getting him through the bottle feeding while Foster Karen took care of momma and his siblings. Great work team! 

Adoption contract and fee applies.  All adoptable dogs can be met at adoption events hosted every weekend. For a list of scheduled events go to: https://www.facebook.com/SmidgetRescue/events .  Smidget Rescue is not a shelter, and dogs cannot be seen at the Rescue location. All dogs are fostered throughout the Puget Sound area and are brought to the events where they can be met by prospective adopters. Additional pictures of adoptable dogs can be seen at: https://www.facebook.com/SmidgetRescue/photos_stream?tab=photos_albums.   All adoptable dogs are spayed or neutered at 6 months of age or older, and always before being placed in their new homes.  APPLICATIONS CAN BE OBTAINED BY EMAIL ONLY. Adoption process includes application, meet & greet, home visit and reference check. Email Jamie at smidgetrescue@hotmail.com or click on the CONTACT link on this page.  PLEASE DOUBLE CHECK YOUR EMAIL ADDRESS BEFORE SENDING.  We get a fair number of incorrect emails and Jamie is not able to contact potential adopters.  Notice:  We do not ship dogs out of state.  If you live within a five-hour radius of Seattle, WA, (such as Portland, Vancouver B.C., etc.), we can arrange for a home visit.  If your home seems like a great fit for the dog you would like to adopt, you must then drive to meet the dog at one of our weekend events or at the fosters home.

DOG'S DESCRIPTION:
Pup Brownie is a sweet little guy who is just a bit unsure of his situation right now, but with some love, understanding, and lots of treats he will soon be your best buddy. Please be sure you have a schedule that will accommodate the needs of a young puppy. They need potty breaks at least every 4 hours, and training to learn good dog manners. Puppies may be a lot of work, but will reward you with a lifetime of love and devotion!
Your new pet will require a refresher in house-training. K-9 Lifesavers strongly recommends all new adopters enroll their new pet into obedience training. This provides for an easier transition into a new home, ensures the dog remains well socialized, and helps form a bond between the dog and the new family.
Adoption fees cover basic vetting, rabies (if puppy is old enough), distemper/parvo vaccinations, treatment for worms, heartworm testing (if puppy is old enough), monthly heartworm prevention while in our care, monthly flea/tick prevention while in our care, and our transport costs. As part of the adoption agreement, adopters agree to get the pup spayed/neutered and provide K-9 Lifesavers with proof of spay/neuter. K-9 Lifesavers does not cover the cost of spay/neuter for puppies 6 months or younger.
Foster Program: Foster homes provide for the temporary care of a rescue until the dog is placed into a loving, forever home. For more information on becoming a foster parent, and our Foster Program, visit http://www.k-9lifesavers.org/foster/ or email our Foster Coordinator at foster@k-9lifesavers.org
Help Save Lives! Make a tax-deductible donation today and help save a life. Donations help us offset boarding costs and additional medical treatment for those dogs who need it. K-9 Lifesavers receives NO federal funding and survive with your generous support! We are all volunteer based organization so every cent from your donation goes directly to the dogs in our care.
For more information on K-9 Lifesavers, or to view a complete listing of all our Adoptable Dogs, visit our website at www.k-9lifesavers.org.
Check out our social media! Search for us on Facebook, Twitter, Pinterest and Instagram!!
Thank you for considering a rescue dog!
SPONSOR ME!
Visit: http://www.k-9lifesavers.org/donate/

Please note due to the current COVID-19 pandemic our adoption process has changed. Please visit our website https://spca.bc.ca/adoption/how-to-adopt/ for more information. All adoptions are by appointment only once we have received an application.

***Due to the high number of applications we receive for our animals, we will only be contacting potential adopters to further review their application. We are not able to call all applicants.***

Current travel restrictions within the province of British Columbia mean that we are prioritizing local (Lower Mainland) adopters at this time. 

--------------------------------------------

Sweet Harriet came into our care after she was surrendered when her owners could no longer care for her. Harriet is a lovely girl, but she can still be a little shy with strangers. Once she knows you, she'll want all the pets and love! Harriet can display some signs of fearfulness so she will need a person who has had dogs before and will have the confidence and knowledge to work with her. She should go to a home where her person is usually around or there are multiple people in the home to keep her company. Because of her fearfulness, Harriet should not go to a home with small children, however older children who are calm and know dogs would be fine. She hasn't lived with other animals, so for consistency, it may be best that Harriet's environment stay that way. Essentially, this girl just needs a loving, dog-savy home where she can be the apple of your eye and be by your side. If you think you can give Harriet the home she's looking for, then fill out an application for her on the BC SPCA website today! Primary Color: Yellow Weight: 28.2kg Age: 1yrs 4mths 0wks

animal.description:
IMPORTANT: Please do not do an inquiry through Petfinder, our volunteers do not have time to reply to the inquiries. Please visit our website to learn more about our adoption process at newhoperescue.org. 

This dog is being fostered with New Hope Dog Rescue (Saskatoon).  If you are interested in adopting please fill out an Adoption Application. Meet and greets are by appointment only and done so after an adoption application has been submitted. A successful applications will be contacted by the foster home to discuss further. We are volunteer run so please be patient.

Meet Chewy the Pug, Chewy is a 4 year old male pug. He’s your typical Pug - loves his humans and very loyal. Chewy’s favourite things are: curled up with his human, walks, car rides and meal time.

Chewy isn’t very active in the home, but does love his walks. He is not interested in toys or other dogs. He’s currently being fostered in a home with two other dogs and a child. He shows no interest in children or the dogs. He has not had any interactions with cats. 

Chewy does mark in the home - he wears a belly band when his foster mama isn’t around. It works great! Chewy is a total love bug - he’s a lap dog who just wants to be near his person!

Chewy has been neutered, microchipped, dewormed, current on age appropriate vaccines and has received a health check from a vet. adoption fee is $295.

To view more dogs go to http://www.newhoperescue.org/adopt/available-dogs/

Disclaimer: in most cases we are guessing the breed mix. These are best guesses on our part. For puppies it can be extremely difficult and we are also guessing on what size they will be. 

NEW HOPE DOG RESCUE is not a shelter. Our dogs are placed in loving foster homes. WE NEED FOSTER HOMES TO HELP MORE DOGS - CONTACT US TODAY!!!
Definitions:
Pending - means that we are working through the adoption process with the 1st applicant. We usually don't add the pending until we are pretty sure the adoption will go through (like at the home visit stage)
Adopted - you know!! A happy ending for a homeless dog.

animal.description:
Meet Eva! This darling Chihuahua mix is looking for a family to call her own. Eva is a playful, spunky girl who loves to play with toys. Eva's forever puppy face, floppy ears, and gentle nature is guaranteed to capture your heart. She is a shy pup, but once you earn her trust, she is happy to show off her friendly, silly personality.

Eva responds well to gentle guidance and structure to help her confidence grow. She has learned to "sit" to ask for what she wants - treats, meal, and even to go outside. She loves to spend her days playing with toys, and enjoys chew bones and is learning how to play fetch and tug-of-war. Eva has lived in a foster home with other dogs her size, and enjoys their company. 

Eva can be very nervous about strangers, and does not hesitate to warn them not to come to close. She would prefer a quiet home without a lot of hustle and bustle. This sweetheart just wants to be with her person, and soak up all the love and attention she can get. If Eva sounds like the right fit for your household, schedule an adoption appointment today!

If you long for some old-fashioned fun with your best pal, Andy might be just the guy to join you! He's an exuberant, athletic, super friendly 10 month old lab/bully breed/mutt who came to CCR from a shelter in Arkansas where he had been found stray. Andy thinks everything is the most fun - and when Andy's around, everything IS the most fun! He'd love an active home where he could get lots of playtime, exercise, and attention. This guy is eager to soak up all the adventure and love you have to offer. He'll do well with other rowdy dogs who don't mind his goofball antics. Because Andy is still a teenager, his new family should plan to give him nice long walks, lots of things to do and think about, and then lots of snuggles at nighttime when he's finally tuckered out! Andy will do well with hearty kids who aren't scared by his big dumb energy! He may even adapt to a confident cat with a nice slow intro.

To meet Andy, please submit an application at chicagocaninerescue.org!

Xavier is a 50 pound, petite, stocky 3 year old pittie mix who came to CCR from a shelter in Arkansas where he had been found stray. animal.description:
Chet is super cute and very sweet.  He likely had a rough start in life and is on the timid side, so he will need a little TLC. He came to us very emaciated. It was discovered that he has EPI, which is relatively common in German Shepherd Dogs. It is easily treated with a pancreatic enzyme power added to his food to help with digestion. Chet is gaining weight and doing great since being on the medication. He's looking for that special home that can give him the love and life that he deserves.
------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
Our Adoption Questionnaire is at http://www.scgsr.org/aq/

About Second Chance German Shepherd Rescue

Second Chance German Shepherd Rescue is a non-profit, volunteer-run, foster-based German Shepherd Dog rescue serving the greater Bay Area and Sacramento/Roseville regions of Northern California. 

Our primary focus is rescuing German Shepherd Dogs from life threatening situations in overcrowded shelters where they are in danger of being put to sleep. We adopt our dogs into loving, responsible permanent homes. German Shepherd Dogs in our care are spayed or neutered, and receive basic veterinary care while they await placement in their permanent homes. We work with area shelters and other rescue groups to develop a network of support for German Shepherd Dogs in need.

SCGSR Adoption Process

We get most of our dogs from the shelters where their previous owners did not provide much training or socialization so they tend to need some training and/or management in order to successfully integrate them into a new household. We have an adoption process to help decide which type of home would be good for the typical dog we get into our rescue. 

Our adoption process is:
Fill out and submit an adoption questionnaire. Have a phone interview. Have an in person home visit - this requires you to be located in one of the following areas where our volunteers live so they can do the required in person home visit: East Bay, South Bay, Peninsula, San Francisco and Marin areas, and in and around the Fresno, Sacramento and Roseville areas. We do not adopt outside of our volunteer area for the safety of our dogs as we need to be able to remove them from a home if things are not working out well e.g. with existing pets.

Adopters who already have had an approved home visit have priority to adopt available dogs. Our adoption fees are $350 for dogs under one year, $300 for dogs one year to six years, and $250 for dogs older than six years. If you do not own your own home your landlord must sign our landlord approval form.  Email us at info@scgsr.org to get our landlord approval form.

Thank you for considering a rescue German Shepherd Dog.

IMPORTANT: Please do not do an inquiry through Petfinder, our volunteers do not have time to reply to the inquiries. Please visit our website to learn more about our adoption process at newhoperescue.org. 

This dog is being fostered with New Hope Dog Rescue (Saskatoon).  If you are interested in adopting please fill out an Adoption Application. Meet and greets are by appointment only and done so after an adoption application has been submitted. A successful applications will be contacted by the foster home to discuss further. We are volunteer run so please be patient.

My name is Eevie and I love to play!  Running and chasing my big foster brother is my favorite thing to do!  I’m working really hard on learning to not go pee in the house, but sometimes I forget.  I like to sleep in my crate all night long but it takes me a few minutes to settle in. I’m learning to walk on a leash and I’m doing pretty good.  I like to watch new things from a distance and will investigate new noises! I love food and need to be separated from my foster brothers or I will try to steal theirs.

Eevie has been microchipped, dewormed, current on age appropriate vaccines and has received a health check from a vet. adoption fee is $495 (200 is refunded upon proof of spay).

To view more dogs go to http://www.newhoperescue.org/adopt/available-dogs/

Disclaimer: in most cases we are guessing the breed mix. These are best guesses on our part. For puppies it can be extremely difficult and we are also guessing on what size they will be. 

NEW HOPE DOG RESCUE is not a shelter. Our dogs are placed in loving foster homes. WE NEED FOSTER HOMES TO HELP MORE DOGS - CONTACT US TODAY!!!
Definitions:
Pending - means that we are working through the adoption process with the 1st applicant. We usually don't add the pending until we are pretty sure the adoption will go through (like at the home visit stage)
Adopted - you know!! A happy ending for a homeless dog.

---

Please know that if you come to meet any of the dogs at our facility, they may be excited to see you and extra active. Many times, this is not a true picture of how they may act in a warm, safe home setting. We, as volunteers, often take our shelter dogs on home visits and they become calm and act like completely different animals. This pertains to bathroom habits and demeanor. Please realize that they need a chance to shine out of the shelter setting!

Please call us at 618-542-DOGS(3647) or if you have any specific questions about me, please email the shelter volunteer at pchsinfo@yahoo.com or go to www.perrycountyhumanesocietyil.com to apply.

animal.description:
Agave is a spunky white pittie mix with the most breathtaking blue eyes. He is about 4 months old and came to us from an extremely high kill shelter where he was dumped outside the shelter with another puppy. Of course, we took them both and they have been loving foster life ever since! 

Agave would probably do best in a house with an older, confident dog so he can learn how to act like a dog and be properly socialized. He would also do best in a cat-free home. Because he is a puppy, he can get very excited and tends to be nippy so older kids or kids who can be respectful towards him and understand that he is still learning would be the best matches for him.  

He is learning all the things he needs to know, including how to love his crate and where the best spots are to sleep! Also, thanks to the snow, he’s learning what dog clothes are! He’s got to stay warm and VISIBLE in all this snow after all! 

Agave is really just an adorable, sweet puppy who loves walks, snow and naps! Think he’d fit in with your life? Fill out a survey at https://www.playersforpits.com/adoption-survey today!

animal.description:
Meet Pearl, a sweet little terrier mix pup. She is 5 months old and still very much a cute pup with lots of energy. 
At 5 weeks old Pearl suffered a massive hernia that pretty much covered her abdomen form top to bottom. We don't know what caused the injury but it was a big surgery for her. As a result we are not sure if she may have any future issues, especially during her spay surgery. 

What does Pearl need.
She needs an experienced home who can work with her through her puppy stage.
A family who will not leave her home alone for long hours, even after COVID
She really loves to run and burn energy and her leash skills are poor, so a home with a secure fenced in yard is a must.
A home with another medium to small dog would be ideal.
No cats

Preference will be given to applicants closer to the Haven and access to our vet.

Pearl is up to date on vaccines, treated for parasites and microchipped. she is also crate trained but needs work on his leash skills
If interested look to the right of your screen and click on the more about Haven of the Heart button, then click on the Adoption Application button.

animal.description:
****Please do not send messages to the rescue asking if a dog is still available; if a dog is still listed on Petfinder, we are still accepting applications for them. PLEASE READ ENTIRE BIO & FAQs BEFORE EMAILING THE RESCUE****

Sugar was rescued from Texas, where there are too many homeless pets and not enough space in shelters to help. She weighs approximately 60 pounds and is estimated to be 2 years of age. She is great with other dogs. She is extremely playful and plays hard. Sugar is completely housebroken, as well as doggie door and crate trained. 

To apply to adopt this dog, visit www.snarrnortheast.org/applications and submit an application. 

-------------------------------------------------------
FAQs -- PLEASE READ ALL BEFORE EMAILING 
**Please note that SNARR NE is a volunteer-based organization. While our volunteers will try to respond to you as quickly as possible, it is helpful if you review the following information about our adoption process before emailing:**

- LISTED BREED(S) & AGE: We are taking our best guess on age, breed, and size when fully grown, based on the puppy's/dog's physical appearance and what we might have learned about one or both parents depending on the situation. *NOTE* We rarely know a dog's exact age, nor are we able to tell the true or full breed mix of dogs as our information is limited most of the time. Because we often do not have access to medical records at the time that we are posting dogs to Petfinder,  there are sometimes discrepancies between the breed that is posted on Petfinder and what might be listed on a dog's medical records.

- SNARR'S ADOPTION PROCESS: The first step in adopting or meeting a SNARR dog/puppy is to fill out an application at www.snarrnortheast.org/applications. Once we receive your application, one of our adoption application processors will contact you, review our adoption process with you, and answer any additional questions you may have. **We do not go on a first-come-first-serve basis for adoptions, but on best fit for a family and most importantly the puppy or dog.**

- MEETING ADOPTABLE DOGS: Meet and greets will not be scheduled until after your adoption application has been fully processed by one of our adoption processors.

- APPLYING ONLINE: If you fill out an online application, please do so from a computer (not a mobile device), make sure you answer ALL the questions in as much detail as possible, and that you receive a confirmation email. If you do not receive a confirmation email, that means we did NOT receive your application.

- PUPPIES: We do suggest listing a 1st, 2nd and 3rd choice on your application if applying for a puppy with several litter mates.

- ADOPTION FEES:  $495 for puppies / $375 for adults. Adoption Fees for Seniors, Special Needs and Bonded Pairs vary

animal.description:
Winnie lost her home because her owner was gravely ill and could not longer care for her.  Winnie is a Miniature Poodle/Terrier Mix whose birthdate is 6-8-16.  Winnie weighs about 16 pounds.  Winnie is healthy and has been spayed, vaccinated, dewormed and microchipped. Winnie is very cute! Look at those ears! She is very sweet and friendly, a great companion dog.  She gets along well with other dogs and cats, but is not used to being around children.
Local adoptions only: within a 75-mile radius of Quail Valley/Menifee, Southwest Riverside County.  Please note: L.A. and Orange Counties are out of area due to traffic/drive time. We deliver adopted animals to their new homes to see where they will be living and see that the yard is safe/secure.

$200 adoption fee, cash only, which is to help reimburse for a portion of expenses of dog rescue and rehabilitation. Adoption contract required. We are looking for adopters who are willing and able to care for this dog for its lifetime (10+ years). We prescreen potential adopters before setting up a meeting.
.
If interested in this dog, please tell us a little about you, your family, your lifestyle, your other pets, your experience as a dog owner (which breed, etc.), where you live and what you are looking for in a dog. Thank you.

Our adoption process involves meeting the animal by appointment. We have the best interest of the animal in mind and our goal is to find a good, permanent home for each of our rescued animals.  We have the right to decline an application if we feel it is not a good match/fit or suitable home. If you like the animal and we both feel it is a good match, an application and adoption contract is completed.  A convenient day/time is arranged for us to deliver the animal to its new home. We will collect the adoption fee (cash only) when we deliver the animal to its new home.  All our adoptions are on a trial basis because our goal is to have a successful adoption where the animal has a good permanent home and never ends up in a bad situation again.  We ask that you give the animal a chance to adjust and settle in his new home and environment.  Going to a new home with new people and a new environment is traumatic and stressful.  It will take time for the animal to become comfortable around you and his/her new home. This should be a bonding period where you get to know the animal and connect with it, spend time with it and take things slow.  He/she will need to get to know and trust you and learn the rules of the house and what is expected of him/her. This takes time, sometimes 2-3 weeks.  During this time we will hold the adoption fee and if the adoption is not working out, we ask that you contact us and return the animal and we will refund your adoption fee.

Meet Herman! He is a 1yr old Yellow Lab pup who was found as a stray. His foster family is starting to see affection from him and he is starting to connect with humans around him. He's not fully housetrained, but his foster mom says he'll learn quickly. He just needs someone who will take time to train him. He's a confident dog. Doesn't jump and knockdown, so foster mom thinks he'd be great with all age kids. He's fine with cats, at least ones that don't run. Herman was just neutered, so he is adjusting to this new side of him. This cutie is a great pup who is playful and energetic but also loves to take naps next to you. Can you give Herman a happy home?

He will come with age-appropriate vaccinations, deworming, neuter, and microchip. His adoption fee is $200.

animal.description:
**Available for Adoption**
Please be within 60-90 minutes of Delmar NY

This handsome, adorable little guy is estimated to be around 2, he’s neutered, fully vetted and crate trained, walks pretty well on a leash. Calm. Medium to lower energy level. 

Calvin is a little bundle of adorable, friendly love, weighing in at 44lbs. 

Calvin found himself in a high kill shelter at no fault of his own, and was on the euthanasia list.  He was in rough shape, 
had heartworm, wounds on his face and was thin.  He has since been fully treated medically, and is finally ready to find his forever home. 
He’s a happy, sweet boy, who’s stranger friendly, dog friendly, and even took up a friendship with a cat. 

He’s sure to bring someone a lot of live, happiness and wonderful companionship. 

If you think this bundle of love, in a smaller package, might be the right match for you, please consider submitting an application, so we can learn more about you.    

———————————-

If you are interested in adopting from GSRNY, please look into our adoption process on our website, and please read below, before contacting us, and please visit our website:

- PLEASE READ THE ENTIRE POST & visit our website BEFORE INQUIRING ABOUT ADOPTION -

All of our dogs are fully vetted before adoption.
Copies of all medical records will go to adopters. 
**Vet appointment dates must be scheduled by adopters and date given to GSRNY before an adoption can take place. 

**Due to the Pandemic Restrictions:
Please be able to print, scan and send all paperwork between you and GSRNY through email in PDF format. 
Have the ability to video your home, inside and out. 
We are thankful for satellite, so we can see your location. 

**Excellent vet history and references are a must. 

**We ask that adopters have plenty of time to work with an adopted dog/puppy. 
Please do keep in mind, your regular work schedule.  The Pandemic has changed schedules for some, but should always be training and preparing for regular work hours & schedules** 

**Our adoption Process may not be for everyone, or the distance too far. Please check out your local shelters and rescues. There are so many animals in need everywhere, we are only one of many.

**If you are considering adopting from GSRNY, please first read through our adoption process, details and fees. If you are still interested in moving forward, you’ll also find our adoption application to download and print out, and send back to us PDF format. 
www.GSRNY.org

animal.description:
www.huskyrescueteam.org

If you have additional questions please email info@huskyrescueteam.orgWelcome Sky to the H-E-A-R-T pack!

Sky was brought to a Georgia Shelter as a stray, with the apparent sign that she had recently had puppies. The Shelter had hoped that an owner would show up for her so they could reunite the puppies with their mother and speak with the owners about her emaciated condition. No such luck.

When no one came for her, H-E-A-R-T did.

She is an absolute doll and her only goal in life is constant hugs and belly rubs! She will need a family who will grant her endless affection and won't leave her for long periods of time, even post COVID. She is curious by nature and non-destructive in the home (so far).

Sky is two years old, spayed, current on her vaccines and healthy. She would be great for a first time Husky owner. Her Adoption area is NJ to NC.

www.huskyrescueteam.org~~Husky Education And Rescue Team is a foster based rescue. Our dogs are in our foster homes all up and down the east coast. We do not have a facility in which you can visit. We find this a huge benefit because we learn our dogs and are able to educate our adopters on what it's like to have them live in your home. Part of our process, once pre-approved, is to speak with the foster for the dog you're interested in. If you're still interested in adopting from our rescue the first step is to complete our adoption application online at www.huskyrescueteam.org/apply

If you have additional questions please email info@huskyrescueteam.org

PLEASE READ THE ENTIRE BIO ON THIS DOG BEFORE REQUESTING AN APPLICATION.  MANY OF OUR DOGS HAVE STRICT REQUIREMENTS FOR THEIR ADOPTION.

8 month old male Chihuahua mix, about 6 pounds. Born May 24, 2020 at the rescue. Trooper (and his brother, Cadet) are a great combination of playful and snuggles. He can race around the house chasing and playing with his brother and the other dogs. But then he can be a super snuggler under the blankets the rest of the time. He is super smart, a tad independent and a bit more active than his brother. He is crate trained, uses the doggie door and is learning about the leash. He is very long legged and a bit on the delicate/fragile side. So jumping from high places should not happen! Young children under 12 are not recommended. Dogs bigger than 12 pounds also not recommended. He is a tad afraid of strangers, but warms up when they become friends.

Adoption contract and fee applies.  All adoptable dogs can be met at adoption events hosted every weekend. For a list of scheduled events go to: https://www.facebook.com/SmidgetRescue/events .  Smidget Rescue is not a shelter, and dogs cannot be seen at the Rescue location. All dogs are fostered throughout the Puget Sound area and are brought to the events where they can be met by prospective adopters. Additional pictures of adoptable dogs can be seen at: https://www.facebook.com/SmidgetRescue/photos_stream?tab=photos_albums.   All adoptable dogs are spayed or neutered at 6 months of age or older, and always before being placed in their new homes.  APPLICATIONS CAN BE OBTAINED BY EMAIL ONLY. Adoption process includes application, meet & greet, home visit and reference check. Email Jamie at smidgetrescue@hotmail.com or click on the CONTACT link on this page.  PLEASE DOUBLE CHECK YOUR EMAIL ADDRESS BEFORE SENDING.  We get a fair number of incorrect emails and Jamie is not able to contact potential adopters.  Notice:  We do not ship dogs out of state.  If you live within a five-hour radius of Seattle, WA, (such as Portland, Vancouver B.C., etc.), we can arrange for a home visit.  If your home seems like a great fit for the dog you would like to adopt, you must then drive to meet the dog at one of our weekend events or at the fosters home.

We would like to (re)introduce Kaia, a 5.5 year old golden retriever mix.  She was adopted in 2015 from us, weighs about 60 lbs and her family has decided they no longer can provide a home for her. 
They now have children, and Kaia has been confusing the childrens toys with those of her own.  Like 50% of dogs, she shows some possession when you try to get them back, but overall they tell us she is a sweet girl, house trained, crate trained, trained with an electric fence and gets along with other dogs if introduced slowly, but should be fed separately as she can be a little bossy sometimes. She loves to be a homebody and does have some car anxiety.  Her ideal home will have dog experience, be willing to provide basic obedience training, doesn’t plan to travel with her frequently, and would make sure to love her unconditionally. A fenced yard is preferred, but not necessary for the right home.  She is located in New England, and we can arrange meet and greets for approved adopters. Say hello to one sweet gal, Dakota is a darling 10 week old, 15 pound mix seeking a special forever family! Dakota is a playful and happy-go-lucky puppy who enjoys playtime and meal time. She is in need of an active home, where she can get lots of interaction, and people to show her the ropes of being a well rounded dog. Dakota is treat motivated and wants to learn. She is a snuggle bug at the end of a long day of play, and will come when you call her for a cozy snooze on the couch. Dakota can't wait to grow and blossom into a wonderful canine companion, won't you be the one to one to show her how? Apply to adopt today!

Interested in adopting? Take the first step and complete an adoption application on our website: http://aarf-tn.com/adopt/adoption-apps/

If you have questions that are not covered in the profile, visit the Pet Inquiry Form: http://aarf-tn.com/contact/pet-inquiry-form/.

THIS PET IS FOSTERED IN TENNESSEE! We do list and adopt our pets nationwide. Typical transport cost to the Northeast is $160. Due to interstate adoption regulations, we are not able to adopt to RI and MA state residents.

A.A.R.F. (All About Rescue and Fixin' Inc.) http://aarf-tn.com/ is a non-profit, 501(c)(3) no kill animal rescue organization located in the Upper Cumberland area of Tennessee. A.A.R.F. is comprised of unpaid volunteers and survives only on public donations. Thank you for thinking adoption first!

Prior to adoption, all canines and felines are spayed or neutered, have received their age appropriate vaccinations, have been de-wormed for common parasites, and have received treatment for prevention of fleas and ticks. All canines over the age of 6 months have been tested for heartworm. All canines are put on heartworm prevention as soon as possible - this means dogs as soon as they are tested negative. Puppies are put on prevention immediately. All felines, regardless of age, have been tested for Feline Leukemia/FIV. Each animal receives a health check by a licensed veterinarian prior to adoption. Anything else found will be treated by our organization prior to adoption.

animal.description:
Pantera is a very handsome, large and gentle soul that is very young at heart. He has one goal in life and that is to love and be loved. He is super sweet and enjoys cuddles. He's housebroken and very good in the house. He gets along with other dogs, but he would do best in a quiet home where he can just relax and "chill" with his people. He enjoys moderate exercise and would probably be fine with a cat with the proper introduction.
------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
Our Adoption Questionnaire is at http://www.scgsr.org/aq/

About Second Chance German Shepherd Rescue

Second Chance German Shepherd Rescue is a non-profit, volunteer-run, foster-based German Shepherd Dog rescue serving the greater Bay Area and Sacramento/Roseville regions of Northern California. 

Our primary focus is rescuing German Shepherd Dogs from life threatening situations in overcrowded shelters where they are in danger of being put to sleep. We adopt our dogs into loving, responsible permanent homes. German Shepherd Dogs in our care are spayed or neutered, and receive basic veterinary care while they await placement in their permanent homes. We work with area shelters and other rescue groups to develop a network of support for German Shepherd Dogs in need.

SCGSR Adoption Process

We get most of our dogs from the shelters where their previous owners did not provide much training or socialization so they tend to need some training and/or management in order to successfully integrate them into a new household. We have an adoption process to help decide which type of home would be good for the typical dog we get into our rescue. 

Our adoption process is:
Fill out and submit an adoption questionnaire. Have a phone interview. Have an in person home visit - this requires you to be located in one of the following areas where our volunteers live so they can do the required in person home visit: East Bay, South Bay, Peninsula, San Francisco and Marin areas, and in and around the Fresno, Sacramento and Roseville areas. We do not adopt outside of our volunteer area for the safety of our dogs as we need to be able to remove them from a home if things are not working out well e.g. with existing pets.

Adopters who already have had an approved home visit have priority to adopt available dogs. Our adoption fees are $350 for dogs under one year, $300 for dogs one year to six years, and $250 for dogs older than six years. If you do not own your own home your landlord must sign our landlord approval form.  Email us at info@scgsr.org to get our landlord approval form.

Thank you for considering a rescue German Shepherd Dog.

She also loves to sleep with her person and even makes nests and snuggles under the covers to stay warm. She does do well with other dogs but has yet to try and play with them. She prefers calmer dogs that don’t jump on her and aren’t too overly hyper. She also does well with cats. 
Ranger is working on potty training and is doing well as long as she is taken out often. She is also HW negative and on preventative, up to date on shots, microchipped, and all healthy and ready to find her forever person/ family. If you are interested in Ranger please fill out an adoption application for consideration found on our website www.cubbyscrusade.org under the forms tab.

animal.description:
You can fill out an adoption application online on our official website.
Name: Chowda
DOB: July 2020
Weight: 25lbs
Adoption Fee: $450

Well hello there! I finally have a name and it is Chowda, I think I like that name. I was so lucky to be rescued by some very nice people in South Dakota as it was getting pretty cold and really hard to find my food. The next thing I knew, I was taking a long trip to Minnesota and this is where I found my new foster parents. I am the luckiest dog ever. I have my own bed and get lots of food. I am actually in a house now! It's so nice and warm. I also got my first warm bath and boy, did I need that.

I love all my attention. My foster mama loves to pet me and snuggle lots. I even get lots of kisses. In my foster home there are two other dogs and I was so excited to play with them, but I still need to learn some manners so I don't get overstimulated. I would love to have some canine playmates in my new home, but slow introductions are a must!

We also have some cats in the house, but my foster mom said no cats for me. I guess I overreact to them a little bit. I just get so excited and really aggressive when I seen them.

I am doing really good with potty training. I can also go on potty pads if you forget to let me out. I do pretty well on a leash but can get distracted once in awhile. I'm still learning. I really didn't know any commands OR manners coming here, so we are working on them and I think I'm getting the hang of things.

My foster mom had her 8 year old granddaughter over and found out I'm not a fan of little ones. I may be better with your kids if they are 10 years or older, I'm just not sure of them. I do love all my adult friends that come and visit. My foster Mama keeps trying to put me in a kennel, (what's up with that). Well, I guess it's part of my learning process, so we are working on it.

Okay guys this about covers it. Who wants to take my cute little baby face and wiggly tail and and give me a forever home?

If you have questions or are interested in me, please fill out an adoption application at www.ruffstartrescue.org.

An adoption application is the best way to show your interest in an animal.

Please check out our website, www.ruffstartrescue.org for more details and additional pictures on any of our animals!

All Ruff Start dogs and cats are spayed/neutered, up to date on age appropriate vaccines, microchipped, dewormed, and on monthly flea/tick and heartworm prevention (dogs) as well as heartworm tested (dogs).

Ruff Start Rescue is a foster based rescue. Animals are located in homes throughout Minnesota. We do not have a facility where animals are kept.

Ruff Start Rescue Adoption Policies: http://www.ruffstartrescue.org/info/display?PageID=11744

animal.description:
PLEASE READ THE ENTIRE BIO ON THIS DOG BEFORE REQUESTING AN APPLICATION.  MANY OF OUR DOGS HAVE STRICT REQUIREMENTS FOR THEIR ADOPTION.

STRICT ADOPTION REQUIREMENTS FOR BLUE:

1.  Needs a 6 foot fence
2.  Needs a buddy his size to play with and learn from.
3.  Children should be 10 y/o or older.

5 month old Lab/Husky mix, about 32 pounds.

Blue is a very sweet, loyal boy who loves to play and be cuddled. He would do best in a home with another dog(s) his size, who will wrestle with him and romp around a spacious FENCED back yard. Blue will play friendly with dogs of any size but he really needs dogs his size. He is friendly with cats and generally leaves them alone - he may be curious and want to sniff them to say hello! He is also friendly with children. He may do better with children that are a bit older (10+) as he will occasionally get excited and jump up (as puppies do!).

Blue is absolutely still a puppy who is learning the basics. He is still teething so he may want to grab your hand but it's never aggressive and he'll quickly stop with a quick "no". His teething isn't destructive by any means (at this point)! He loves stuffed toys and hasn't ripped any, so far. He’s working on crate and potty training but has already made quite a bit of progress. He’ll need a patient family that will continue to work with him on it. As of now, he has a bit of separation anxiety when left alone. He is not destructive, he just cries, VERY loudly. Because of this behavior, we MUST place him in a home without close neighbors. This will get better with a concerted effort to train him to be alone and self soothe. However, this will take some time, so let's not upset the neighbors right away! Also, with his Northern breed heritage, he will need a fenced no shorter than 6 feet. He is very food motivated and will sit, lay, and come over when called for a treat. He is the sweetest boy and would make the absolute best addition to a family who will give him the love, training, and attention he so greatly deserves. 

Adoption contract and fee applies.  All adoptable dogs can be met at adoption events hosted every weekend. For a list of scheduled events go to: https://www.facebook.com/SmidgetRescue/events .  Smidget Rescue is not a shelter, and dogs cannot be seen at the Rescue location. All dogs are fostered throughout the Puget Sound area and are brought to the events where they can be met by prospective adopters. Additional pictures of adoptable dogs can be seen at: https://www.facebook.com/SmidgetRescue/photos_stream?tab=photos_albums.   All adoptable dogs are spayed or neutered at 6 months of age or older, and always before being placed in their new homes.  APPLICATIONS CAN BE OBTAINED BY EMAIL ONLY. Adoption process includes application, meet & greet, home visit and reference check. Email Jamie at smidgetrescue@hotmail.com or click on the CONTACT link on this page.  PLEASE DOUBLE CHECK YOUR EMAIL ADDRESS BEFORE SENDING.  We get a fair number of incorrect emails and Jamie is not able to contact potential adopters.  Notice:  We do not ship dogs out of state.  If you live within a five-hour radius of Seattle, WA, (such as Portland, Vancouver B.C., etc.), we can arrange for a home visit.  If your home seems like a great fit for the dog you would like to adopt, you must then drive to meet the dog at one of our weekend events or at the fosters home.

animal.description:
This puppy is a mixed breed puppy; the breed of their parents is unknown. They will likely be medium-large when full grown. As with all puppies, this puppy would greatly benefit from positive reinforcement training, socialization, and enrichment.

PLEASE READ CAREFULLY:
Puppies sure are cute but they require a tremendous amount of time and commitment. Before applying to adopt a puppy, please consider if you are able to provide for everything a puppy will need to grow into a healthy, socialized adult dog. Things to consider before applying to adopt a puppy:

1.Time Commitment: How much time do you have to devote to the puppy and are you willing to commit to the dog for its life? From training, to multiple feedings daily, to middle of the night potty trips, puppies need constant attention and cannot be left alone for long periods of time. If you cannot devote time to properly and responsibly raise the puppy, then it's not the time to bring a puppy home.

2. Socialization: This job is critical of a puppy owner, and is especially important in the first few months of life. Can you commit the time to socialize your puppy? Puppies need to be meet people and other dogs to become a well-adjusted and confident adult dog. Socialization is never complete in a dog, but the longer you wait the harder it gets.

3. Housing: It's seemingly a simple question, but is overlooked or ignored by many. Can you properly house a puppy and are you allowed to have a puppy? Renters: Check your lease to see if there are pet restrictions. Home Owners: Check your home owner's insurance policy for restrictions. Every year thousands of dogs are returned because they were not allowed - this is not fair to the animal or to you, so please make sure that there are no issues if you bring home a puppy.

4. Lifestyle: What is your lifestyle like? Are you an active family that spends plenty of time outdoors? Or are you more of a couch potato? Some dogs require a lot of exercise daily, and remember that small does not equal less energy. Some large breed dogs have a lower activity level than many smaller breeds.

5. Cost: Can you afford a puppy? Food, veterinary visits, vaccinations, training, licensing and medical emergencies. Just a few of the costs to consider, and remember the costs of owning an animal need to be maintained for its entire life.

6. Patience/Training: Are you a patient person? Puppies are of course babies and need to learn in order to become a well-adjusted adult. Remember it takes time and lots of patience! House training, crate training, obedience training, how to walk properly on a leash; these are just a few of the critical training areas. If you lack patience and get frustrated quickly, then maybe an older dog would be better for you.

7. Long Term: What will happen to the dog if you start a family? What if you have to move? Again there are thousands that are given up every year for these reasons. Dogs are a lifetime commitment, and plans for these factors need to be made to ensure that the dog remains a part of the family for the next 10-15 years.

8. Human Medical Issues: Are there any allergies or medical conditions in your family that could cause issues that may result in having to surrender the puppy? If there are suspected health concerns, consult a doctor before considering any pet.

9. Grooming: All dogs need grooming - even hairless breeds! There's brushing as well as regular attention to teeth, ears and nails. Some breeds do require professional grooming, while others may require a few minutes with a brush on a weekly basis. Are you able to handle this responsibility?

10. Need: Finally - Why do you want a puppy? If you already have pets in the house, especially senior pets, they may not be crazy about the idea of having a rambunctious puppy running around. Along with current pets, consider other family members too and who will care the dog for its entire life, not just its formative years. If a puppy may not be the best fit for you and your family, be sure to consider one of the many, many adult dogs waiting in our shelters!

IMPORTANT: Please note that we receive a high volume of applications for puppies. Our team is incredibly busy reviewing all applications and will contact you as soon as possible if your application has been approved. Please do not contact our shelters regarding the status of your application. 

TRAINING AND SOCIALIZATION:
Puppies require time, patience, and commitment to help them grow into happy, healthy adult dogs. To give the full commitment that puppies need, we do not permit adopters to adopt more than 1 puppy, of the same age or from the same litter. While it may seem cute, and even easier, to adopt 2 puppies at the same time, research shows that it's not a good idea. Littermate Syndrome can occur when 2 puppies are raised together. Their deep bond can impede their ability to properly socialize with humans and other dogs during this critical developmental period which can lead to behavioral issues as adult dogs, including reactivity and aggression. Please also consider force free, science-based training to help your new puppy become a happy, well socialized family member that won't end up back at our shelter. To find a trainer on island, visit fearfreepets.com or apdt.com.
