animal.description:
This puppy is a mixed breed puppy; the breed of their parents is unknown. They will likely be medium-large when full grown. As with all puppies, this puppy would greatly benefit from positive reinforcement training, socialization, and enrichment.

PLEASE READ CAREFULLY:
Puppies sure are cute but they require a tremendous amount of time and commitment. Before applying to adopt a puppy, please consider if you are able to provide for everything a puppy will need to grow into a healthy, socialized adult dog. Things to consider before applying to adopt a puppy:

1.Time Commitment: How much time do you have to devote to the puppy and are you willing to commit to the dog for its life? From training, to multiple feedings daily, to middle of the night potty trips, puppies need constant attention and cannot be left alone for long periods of time. If you cannot devote time to properly and responsibly raise the puppy, then it's not the time to bring a puppy home.

2. Socialization: This job is critical of a puppy owner, and is especially important in the first few months of life. Can you commit the time to socialize your puppy? Puppies need to be meet people and other dogs to become a well-adjusted and confident adult dog. Socialization is never complete in a dog, but the longer you wait the harder it gets.

3. Housing: It's seemingly a simple question, but is overlooked or ignored by many. Can you properly house a puppy and are you allowed to have a puppy? Renters: Check your lease to see if there are pet restrictions. Home Owners: Check your home owner's insurance policy for restrictions. Every year thousands of dogs are returned because they were not allowed - this is not fair to the animal or to you, so please make sure that there are no issues if you bring home a puppy.

4. Lifestyle: What is your lifestyle like? Are you an active family that spends plenty of time outdoors? Or are you more of a couch potato? Some dogs require a lot of exercise daily, and remember that small does not equal less energy. Some large breed dogs have a lower activity level than many smaller breeds.

5. Cost: Can you afford a puppy? Food, veterinary visits, vaccinations, training, licensing and medical emergencies. Just a few of the costs to consider, and remember the costs of owning an animal need to be maintained for its entire life.

6. Patience/Training: Are you a patient person? Puppies are of course babies and need to learn in order to become a well-adjusted adult. Remember it takes time and lots of patience! House training, crate training, obedience training, how to walk properly on a leash; these are just a few of the critical training areas. If you lack patience and get frustrated quickly, then maybe an older dog would be better for you.

7. Long Term: What will happen to the dog if you start a family? What if you have to move? Again there are thousands that are given up every year for these reasons. Dogs are a lifetime commitment, and plans for these factors need to be made to ensure that the dog remains a part of the family for the next 10-15 years.

8. Human Medical Issues: Are there any allergies or medical conditions in your family that could cause issues that may result in having to surrender the puppy? If there are suspected health concerns, consult a doctor before considering any pet.

9. Grooming: All dogs need grooming - even hairless breeds! There's brushing as well as regular attention to teeth, ears and nails. Some breeds do require professional grooming, while others may require a few minutes with a brush on a weekly basis. Are you able to handle this responsibility?

10. Need: Finally - Why do you want a puppy? If you already have pets in the house, especially senior pets, they may not be crazy about the idea of having a rambunctious puppy running around. Along with current pets, consider other family members too and who will care the dog for its entire life, not just its formative years. If a puppy may not be the best fit for you and your family, be sure to consider one of the many, many adult dogs waiting in our shelters!

IMPORTANT: Please note that we receive a high volume of applications for puppies. Our team is incredibly busy reviewing all applications and will contact you as soon as possible if your application has been approved. Please do not contact our shelters regarding the status of your application. 

TRAINING AND SOCIALIZATION:
Puppies require time, patience, and commitment to help them grow into happy, healthy adult dogs. To give the full commitment that puppies need, we do not permit adopters to adopt more than 1 puppy, of the same age or from the same litter. While it may seem cute, and even easier, to adopt 2 puppies at the same time, research shows that it's not a good idea. Littermate Syndrome can occur when 2 puppies are raised together. Their deep bond can impede their ability to properly socialize with humans and other dogs during this critical developmental period which can lead to behavioral issues as adult dogs, including reactivity and aggression. Please also consider force free, science-based training to help your new puppy become a happy, well socialized family member that won't end up back at our shelter. To find a trainer on island, visit fearfreepets.com or apdt.com.

animal.description:
Victor is a very handsome and large young boy. He is super sweet and very affectionate. He loves being with people, playing ball and tug and going for walks. Victor walks very nice on a leash, he is housebroken, crate trained and rides well in the car. He gets along with other dogs but enjoys rough play. Victor is very smart and inquisitive. As a young dog, he would benefit from a home with large breed experience that will continue his training and give him lots of exercise and mental stimulation. 

------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
Our Adoption Questionnaire is at http://www.scgsr.org/aq/

About Second Chance German Shepherd Rescue

Second Chance German Shepherd Rescue is a non-profit, volunteer-run, foster-based German Shepherd Dog rescue serving the greater Bay Area and Sacramento/Roseville regions of Northern California. 

Our primary focus is rescuing German Shepherd Dogs from life threatening situations in overcrowded shelters where they are in danger of being put to sleep. We adopt our dogs into loving, responsible permanent homes. German Shepherd Dogs in our care are spayed or neutered, and receive basic veterinary care while they await placement in their permanent homes. We work with area shelters and other rescue groups to develop a network of support for German Shepherd Dogs in need.

SCGSR Adoption Process

We get most of our dogs from the shelters where their previous owners did not provide much training or socialization so they tend to need some training and/or management in order to successfully integrate them into a new household. We have an adoption process to help decide which type of home would be good for the typical dog we get into our rescue. 

Our adoption process is:
Fill out and submit an adoption questionnaire. Have a phone interview. Have an in person home visit - this requires you to be located in one of the following areas where our volunteers live so they can do the required in person home visit: East Bay, South Bay, Peninsula, San Francisco and Marin areas, and in and around the Fresno, Sacramento and Roseville areas. We do not adopt outside of our volunteer area for the safety of our dogs as we need to be able to remove them from a home if things are not working out well e.g. with existing pets.

Adopters who already have had an approved home visit have priority to adopt available dogs. Our adoption fees are $350 for dogs under one year, $300 for dogs one year to six years, and $250 for dogs older than six years. If you do not own your own home your landlord must sign our landlord approval form.  Email us at info@scgsr.org to get our landlord approval form.

Thank you for considering a rescue German Shepherd Dog.

animal.description:
Meet Tyson, this adorable FEMALE Spaniel/Terrier mix is a gorgeous girl. Tyson was so nervous when she can in that our staff was not able to tell if she was a boy or a girl. Tyson was brought in because her owner passed away and there was no family available to take her in. Tyson is understandably nervous with new situations but quickly warms up with loving care and attention.
Tyson currently weighs in at 21 pounds. Tyson has not received any training or must socialization. She is in need of an adopter that can give her a safe and calm environment.
If you are interested in adopting this pet please fill out an adoption questionnaire at www.yakimahumane.org. A Yakima Humane Society staff member will contact you once your questionnaire has been received.

If you would like to adopt this pet you can fill out an online adoption form at www.yakimahumane.org. Please give the name and ID number for the animal you wish to adopt.
If you are thinking about adding a pet to your family, be a hero, please consider adopting a shelter pet and if you already have pets – for life’s sake – spay and neuter. Spaying and neutering your pets is the single most important thing you can do to help decrease our nations severe pet overpopulation.
*NOTE: Nearly 90% of the animals that come into our shelter are abandoned, neglected, traumatized, injured, or ill. We attempt to give our best assessment of the animal’s welfare and temperament. Unfortunately, due to lack of funding, volunteers, and resources our physical and mental assessment of the animal is not always 100% correct.

animal.description:
Penny is a super sweet & affectionate Staffy/Boston Terrier mix who is 2 years old and weighs 40 lbs.  She is a happy, curious, social girl who warms up to new people quickly and likes to please her humans.  She is not currently living with young kids or other dogs in her foster home, but she is attracted to kids and other dogs on walks and always approaches in a polite & friendly manner.  She has good leash manners, responds well to verbal corrections, and is impressing her foster family with how quickly she learns basic commands.  She is a medium energy, intelligent girl who loves to chase a ball, will play hard for short periods, but then fatigues and is ready for her cuddles & snuggles on the couch with her family.  She's a cautious, thoughtful girl who can often be seen with one ear up & one down while she ponders something new or hears an unfamiliar sound.  She is spayed, fully vaccinated, microchipped, and is currently being housebroken & crate trained in her foster home.  Her foster family adores her and knows she will be a wonderful, loving, devoted companion for the lucky person/family who adopts her!

For more information about Penny, please email us at info@barkvilledogrescue.org. If you would like to adopt this sweet girl, please submit an application for her at https://www.barkvilledogrescue.org/applications

animal.description:
You can fill out an adoption application online on our official website.
KLINE is a very sweet young blue and white pit bull terrier boy who came to us as a result of an animal cruelty case. He is a gentle, loving puppy, about 9 months old and 50 lbs. He's fully grown but needs to add about 5 lbs. Kline is a personable, playful young dog who loves people of all ages, other dogs and is fine with cats. You can see some signs of the cruelty Kline endured in these photos. Here's what we know this boy endured: his ears were mangled and infected. Someone cut one ear off, the other was ripped off. He had infected bite wounds on his face. He has lumps and bumps on his body from beatings. He was under-nourished. We've been told he was hung at some point. BUT the person who tried to break this dog failed. Kline charms everyone he meets with his sweet, boyish, playful disposition. Thankfully an Animal Control Officer is pursuing charges against the person who rained hell on this precious doggo. We hope Kline gets the justice he deserves. More importantly, we want Kline to find the loving furever home he needs. If you'd like to meet this very special young dog, please fill out a foster-to-adopt application at
dreamhouserescue.org.
Greater Cincinnati-area adopters only please.

All of our fully-vetted adoptable dogs go to prospective homes for a one-week trial foster-to-adopt period to make sure the dog and home are the right fit before an adoption is finalized. We only adopt dogs into homes where all current pets are spayed/neutered and current on vaccines and heartworm and flea and tick prevention. We do check veterinary references to make sure adopters are compliant with standard veterinary care.

ATTENTION: All of our dogs are in private foster homes. We do NOT have a kennel with multiple dogs. If you find a dog you want to meet in person, please go to www.secondchancedogrescue.org and complete an application. We will make every attempt to process all applications within 3 business days of receipt.

// //
Meet Rosemary! She is a super sweet playful, 70 pound, Shepherd Collie Mix. After giving birth to 6 beautiful puppies 12 weeks ago she is ready to find her forever home. (She was an awesome mom too!) Rosemary loves to play with other dogs and people. She is good with children as well as dogs of all sizes. While in foster care she was not with kitties so that relationship is unknown. She is potty trained and walks ok on the leash. She does well in the car but can be a bit nervous getting in and out of your vehicle. She doesn't much like water but did well when she got groomed recently. Rosemary is pretty quiet but will bark when she is lonely. Rosemary would do best in a home where there are people and other critters to keep her company. Since she is a large hairy dog she will require a large space, fair amount of food and regular grooming. Rosemary is spayed, micro chipped and current on her vaccines. Her adoption fee is $300.

All Second Chance Dog Rescue dogs are spayed/neutered, are up to date on vaccines and have microchips prior to adoption.

Adoption fees vary depending on age of dog. Fees help Second Chance Dog Rescue cover spay/neuter costs,

vaccinations, medical treatments,

food and supplies. Please go to

www.secondchancedogrescue.org

and complete an application today!

All dogs live in private foster homes until they are adopted.

animal.description:
Hi! My name is Duchess, and I am ready for my furever home. I am about 1 1/2 years old, and am a very sweet girl. Until I came to my foster home a few weeks ago, I had never had a collar or leash. Now, I am learning to walk with a harness (I can pull a collar off with no problem, haha) and am really enjoying walks around the neighborhood. I have a foster brother and a foster sister who love to run and play with me in the yard. Lately, I have discovered mulch bags back there which are really fun to rip up and drag around the yard! I also like to chew nylabones and real bones. Squeaky toys are really fun. I can squeak them really loud sometimes. I also, really like to play outside. My foster sister and I play chase, I’m faster than her, but she is a lot bigger than I am. I like to sit outside and watch squirrels and birds too. A fenced yard will be helpful. I have recently been spayed. Also, I had two different kinds of worms and I tested positive for Lyme Disease, so I’m still taking medications for that. My health is really good now.I need a really special family to adopt me. I am shy, and might run from you at first. Right now, I’m not very motivated by food. I won’t take treats from your hand, but I like them if you just put it close to me and walk away. I sleep in a crate beside my foster parents’ bed, and when I wake up in the morning, I need to go outside right away. I’m a really good sleeper though. If you think I would be a good match for your family, I hope you will apply to adopt me. I’m very affectionate, and I have the sweetest smile!

Please see recommendations and requirements at KGDR.org and apply at https://www.shelterluv.com/matchme/adopt/KGDR/Dog

Due to COVID-19 precautions, all animals for adoption through Homeward Trails can be met by appointment only. You can make an appointment to meet available dogs at our ADOPTION CENTER by going to https://www.signupgenius.com/go/20f084ea8ae2da5f49-meet and available cats at MEOW PALACE by going to https://www.signupgenius.com/go/20f084ea8ae2da5f49-meet1. 
For animals in FOSTER homes, please submit an online application and an adoption team will reply with next steps. We thank you for your patience as we work to keep saving lives during this difficult time. 

PLEASE VISIT THIS WEBSITE TO FIND THE ADOPTION QUESTIONNAIRE: http://www.homewardtrails.org/adopt-a-pet/adoption-forms/

This sweet girl is Britta. Britta spent the first year of her life chained outside. Now this 1 year old is looking for a forever home that is willing to give her the life she deserves and help her learn her manners. Britta is a strong 1 year old Lab/Shepherd mix who is good with other dogs.

Adoption Coordinator: Adoption Center
Location: Adoption Center

The adoption fee for this dog/puppy is $475. This fee includes spay/neuter and microchip. 

We are proud to partner with the following veterinarians who offer a free first exam for your animal, exclusively for HT adopters: Caring Hands Animal Hospital, Palisades Veterinary Clinic, Sunshine Animal Hospital and Clarendon Animal Care and all VCA Animal Hospitals.

Additionally, any VCA hospital will cover illnesses up to $250 at no cost to any Homeward Trails adopter.

 We also provide free online workshop with a professional dog trainer at Fur-Get Me Not within the first 30 days of adopting - just for HT adopters in the Arlington/Alexandria/Falls Church/DC area. Start your new dog out on the right foot with this valuable, expert guidance FREE!

You can save animals like this one by becoming a foster! Fosters are like way stations between high kill shelters and forever homes. We need fosters so that we can save dogs before they are euthanized at the shelters. If you are interested in becoming a foster, please check out our information about fostering by visiting http://www.homewardtrails.org/foster-a-pet/dog-and-cat-foster-program

animal.description:
Meet Jovoni, this handsome 2-year-old male Spaniel/Terrier mix who is ready for a forever home. He is a fun bigger-small dog, weighing in at 23 pounds. Jovoni's owner sadly passed away and there was no family able to take him in. Understandably Jovoni has had a little trouble adapting to his new situation and can be very nervous. He needs a loving and quiet home that will help him feel safe and loved. Jovoni is not leash trained and does not appear to be potty trained. His adopter will need to be patient and understanding while training, luckily Jovoni is treat-motivated.
If you are interested in adopting this pet please fill out an adoption questionnaire at www.yakimahumane.org. A Yakima Humane Society staff member will contact you once your questionnaire has been received.

If you would like to adopt this pet you can fill out an online adoption form at www.yakimahumane.org. Please give the name and ID number for the animal you wish to adopt.
If you are thinking about adding a pet to your family, be a hero, please consider adopting a shelter pet and if you already have pets – for life’s sake – spay and neuter. Spaying and neutering your pets is the single most important thing you can do to help decrease our nations severe pet overpopulation.
*NOTE: Nearly 90% of the animals that come into our shelter are abandoned, neglected, traumatized, injured, or ill. We attempt to give our best assessment of the animal’s welfare and temperament. Unfortunately, due to lack of funding, volunteers, and resources our physical and mental assessment of the animal is not always 100% correct.

animal.description:
Rain has spent her short life outside tethered with a heavy chain. She has already had several litters. After her last litter, her owners allowed her to be surrendered into rescue.

This adorable 26 pound hound mix would thrive in a quiet home where she can learn how to be a dog. She is a very affectionate and follows her person everywhere. Rain also plays well with other dogs and cats too!!! She also does well with calmer children.

Rain has been housetrained at her foster home and will go to the door when she needs to potty. She has done very well on a leash and is non-reactive to dogs while walking. 

Rain is not a big fan of the crate, but will settle in if coerced with treats. She has not been left alone too much, but has been trustworthy when alone. She is not yet interested in toys and does need to learn how to play.

This special girl is a doll. She is very accommodating and sweet and will bond quickly with her new family. Her adopter should have the time to spend with her as she transitions to become an indoor loved pet. It truly will be a rewarding experience.

Check out her video: https://youtu.be/BlePJo2Vlw8


Name: Rain
Breed: Hound/Terrier Mix
Sex: Female
Age: 1 1/2 yrs (estimate)
Weight: 26 lbs.
Spayed/Neutered: Yes
Vaccinations: Up to date
Heartworm: Negative
Microchipped: Yes

BASED ON OUR OBSERVATIONS:
Good with Children: Calmer older children, small kids or toddlers may be too much for her.
Good with Dogs: Yes
Good with Cats: Yes

Adoption Fee: $475.00

IMPORTANT INFORMATION:
Interested in a specific dog, please fill out an application if you are interested in a dog. The number of individual inquiries is overwhelming and we are finding it difficult to respond to each one. We cannot guarantee you will receive a timely response.

Paws New England is a rescue, not a shelter, and as such we do not have our dogs housed in one location - they are in foster homes both in New England and in our southern foster homes. If you're interested in a specific dog, please complete a short online application and you will receive a reply within 48 hours so you can ask questions.

At present, if a dog is listed on our website, the dog is considered still available HOWEVER, may have applications that have come in before yours but it's still too early to know if any are a good match; therefore we encourage you to apply.

NOTICE WITH REGARD TO LOCATION OF DOGS: Please note: Paws New England is a foster-based rescue. We do not have a brick and mortar building to house the dogs we rescue. We have found that dogs in foster homes are much more adoptable because they have been observed in a home setting. Dogs listed with Paws New England typically reside in various locations throughout the south (primarily Tennessee, Texas, and Arkansas) and New England (not necessarily in the state of Rhode Island). You will be notified by the adoption coordinator of the location of the dog you are interested in so you have the ability to decide whether to pursue adoption or not.

Dogs transported to New England are done so at a fee of $150.00 paid directly to the transporting company by Paws New England; no additional transport costs are responsibility of adopter. This fee is included in the adoption donation.

Adoption donations cover pre-adoption vet costs (including vaccinations, spay/neuter when age appropriate, and heartworm testing/treatment when necessary), a microchip, and transportation to New England if necessary.

Donations for our young, healthy puppies and dogs support their fellow canines of advanced age or suffering from injuries and abuse whose donations are reduced but whose veterinary costs are typically much higher. We appreciate your understanding that your dog will help others in need.

All known information about the animal is listed above. We do our best to give accurate information, but most of our dogs are rescues and do not come with a known history.

Paws New England abides by the dog importation regulations set forth in the states of MA, CT, NH and RI.

animal.description:
Sundae - as sweet as an ice cream treat with a cherry on top!

This little one's sad beginnings in life are easy to see as it's right here on Facebook https://www.facebook.com/mrz.becton/posts/4345525092141081
Sundae was living outside (sun, rain, snow, hot or cold) in a crate that was way too small for her and surviving on trash as her meals. One of our friends in Memphis was so awesome and managed to get this girl away from her family and into Paws New England and she is now with a foster family in New England.

Sundae is a sweetheart and loves nothing more than to be with her person. Sundae is just a puppy at heart who does not realize that she has gotten big - she never got a chance to be a puppy. Sundae wants to be on her person, near her person, with her person always, so she is working on independence in her foster home. Sundae is doing well with asking for attention by either sitting or laying down to be patted. Sundae is funny, spunky and smart but will need someone who will take the lead. Someone with previous breed experience or large dog experience is a MUST. Sundae has a nice on/off switch and will require exercise but with proper exercise she is just as happy to sit on the couch and veg with you. Sundae is working on her leash manners - again, she never got out to see the world and gets excited to go but is learning that when you pull, you will not get anywhere. Stop pulling and you get to keep exploring!

Sundae is fostering with several canine foster siblings. While Sundae can be around the other dogs, she is protective of her bed, crate, treats and toys so we feel best that she is only placed in a home without another animal. Poor Sundae probably went days without being fed, eating garbage when she was fed and without a comfy place to rest, so being protective of things you never had is understandable. Sundae is not protective of these things with people. 

Sundae is very deserving of family that will help her be her best self. Sundae needs someone who will dedicate time daily for her training. Sundae is crate trained and is doing wonderfully with her housebreaking. Because of Sundae's size and strength, we are asking for a home without kids or kids only over 12 who are dog savvy and can help with the consistency in training that will be required for Sundae's continued growth. With a little training, structure, love, warm comfy bed inside and a food bowl that has food that magically appears, she will no doubt be an amazing lifelong companion.

animal.description:
Hi! Lucy Rose here.  I am a Doberman mix and weigh 55 lbs. I am about 3 years. I previously lived with a family that was forced to move due to financial difficulties and they weren’t able to take me with them.  I am house trained and don’t mind a kennel although I don’t really need one. I’m spayed , current on all vaccinations, microchipped, and heart worm negative. My foster family already has dogs and we love playing together.  My foster dad calls me one of his co-workers because I like to sit by him and nap while he works from home. I would love if my future owners has dogs too but I am not going to be picky as long as they take me on walks and preferably have some outdoor space to run around.  I am super smart and pick up on things really quick.  While I am having a great time at my foster parents place, I am ready for my forever family!

*Take Paws Rescue saves dogs from high-kill shelters in Southeast Louisiana, owner surrenders, and discarded dogs with uncertain futures. All of our puppies live in foster homes where they are socialized, and well cared for. An application will be required to make sure it’s the perfect match!

 If you are interested in meeting and/or adopting, the first step is to please visit our website to complete an application and read all of our FAQs: https://www.takepawsrescue.org/adopt 

**An inquiry/question on Petfinder is NOT an application. All known details about our animals are posted on their profile and updated daily. Other info would be discussed in detail with the foster during the application review process. Due to the number of inquires received (hundreds daily) we ask you submit an application on our website (a single application can be used for any dog with Take Paws Rescue).

The adoption fee for adult dogs covers age appropriate vaccinations, microchip, spay/neuter if not yet performed, heartworm test & appropriate heartworm treatment by the rescue's vet. All dogs in our care are also kept up-to-date on HW/Flea Prevention. Please see our website for more information. 

2021 Adoption Fee Scale for non-benefactor animals:
Puppies under 12 months - $300
Dogs over 12 months - $200

animal.description:
We are so pleased for you to meet the lovely "LUNA" aka. Blue bear!

This absolutely beautiful pup is a 7-month old, 45lb, mixed breed girl who has the sweetest face, floppiest of ears and loving personality! 

BACKGROUND:
Luna's original owners found her and decided to raise her in their home, alongside their two other doggy companions. Unfortunately one of their dogs wasn't getting along so well with Luna and she's needing a new forever home!  

PERSONALITY & BEHAVIOR:
Luna is an affectionate cutie, who likes to the company of other dogs and humans! She loves toys (especially snoozing with them!) and is very playful and happy. She's very good at being attuned to her humans and is willing to play, go for walks or relax on the sofa whenever YOU are ready! Being a younger dog Luna may still need some additional training (house, crate, leash-walking), but she's an eager learner who wants to do nothing but please!  

Additionally, she is up to date on all vaccinations and is scheduled to be spayed very soon!  She's ready to become a part of your family today!

If you’d like more information or are interested in this precious girl, please text 4-6 photo's of your interior/exterior home and yard (including fence if applicable) to Judy (423-718-0939).

- - - 

Please Note: Inquiries through Pet Finder may be slower to respond and the best form of communication/inquiry would be through text message at the number above. Thank you.

Ranger is a super sweet and loving approximately 7 yr old 10lb  spayed female Chihuahua & Toy Fox Terrier mix. She is great with all people and yearns for affection/ attention  so would do best in a home where someone is not gone for long hours at a time. She is definitely a lap dog/ cuddle buddy/ partner in crime who wants nothing more then to be by her persons side.  She also loves to sleep with her person and even makes nests and snuggles under the covers to stay warm. She does do well with other dogs but has yet to try and play with them. If you are interested in Ranger please fill out an adoption application for consideration found on our website www.cubbyscrusade.org under the forms tab.

animal.description:
Rudy and Stitch are looking for a home together, they lost their last home due to a death.  They have been together since Rudy was a puppy, he is now about 3.5 years old and Stitch is 5 years old.  Rudy is super sweet little black Chiweenie and Stitch is the Golden Pom mix.  Stitch is a bit more reserved when he first meets you but as soon as Rudy says it’s ok, he is a great little guy.  Both love snuggles and love their humans, they also get along with other dogs.  They would make great walking pups.  They still like to play and Stitch loves his naps.  They are crate trained and sleep together.  When their companion died they were due to be euthanized by the rest of the family who were against their parent having dogs in the first place.  These two little guys were not only a companion to their human, but family.  They have been through quite a change, when a rescue reached out and asked us to take them we, of course, said yes.  The family found out that they were going to a rescue and took the dogs to another shelter in Texas to have them euthanized.  We are happy to say that shelter reached out to us and we were so happy to have found them and rescued them.  Rudy and Stitch had a lot of people in Texas helping them find their way to Colorado, despite what their “family” wanted.  They are the sweetest guys in the world and deserve a second chance for a home and a life.  If you would like to meet Rudy and Stitch please fill out an application at

www.lowridersofthewest.org

Rudy and Stitch’s adoption fee is $600.00 - they are neutered, up to date on all their vaccinations and chipped.

animal.description:
Maurice is living in a foster home. Submit an application from our website and then make an appointment to meet him.

Maurice is not eligible for foster and will be a straight adoption.

Age: ~1 year
Weight: ~39lbs (should gain some)
Housebroken: Working on it! He needs to be on a strict schedule
Crate trained: Working on it! Takes some time to settle (10-30 minutes) and will benefit from continued training for this. 
Dog sociability: Selective with his dog pals. Maurice previously lived in a foster home with a dog and did well, but resource guarded toys/food with another dog in another home. We think he would do best as a solo dog in his forever home, but he would likely be a good candidate for doggy daycare for continued socialization. On walks, he will be frustrated and may bark/lunge/pull at other dogs in an effort to say 'hi!'
Cat sociability: Unknown
Kids: Not a match for young kids due to his mouthy behavior. May do okay with teenagers.
Ideal home: Maurice is a young, energetic guy that will thrive with an active home that can work on training for adolescent behaviors! He'd love to be enrolled into training right away and would benefit from going to daycare to help exert some energy. 

 V.G.B. (Very Good Boy) ALERT! Maurice is a loyal little ball of energy that is ready to find his forever home. He would love to find somebody who could continue stimulating his curiosity as he learns new tricks and explores new places on walks. As a V.G.B., Maurice is ready to learn new tricks and be that loyal companion who will be by his owner's side through the good and the "ruff". Maurice was most likely an actor in a previous life because he loves to be center stage and is not afraid to let you know what he wants. He is a quick learner and a lover of all people who just wants to be held like the baby he is. He has learned 'paw', 'down', and 'wait' in his current foster and will thrive with an adopter that is dedicated to getting him into training right away. 

Maurice's adoption fee is 300. He is neutered, up to date on core vaccines, microchipped and heartworm negative. He will require booster vaccines at the adopter's expense. 

***We are receiving a much higher than usual number of adoption applications. We ask that you please be patient and someone will be in touch via email within 72 hours. Please do not email us unless you have not received a response in 72 hours. Please only fill out one adoption application. ***
